The paper focuses on automatic understanding of human affect using visual signals, which falls under computer vision (cs.CV) and machine learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. The paper also discusses the design and training of a deep neural architecture for affect prediction, which is a popular topic in artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Additionally, the paper mentions the use of datasets and challenges for evaluating affect recognition algorithms, which could fall under human-computer interaction (cs.HC) and multimedia (cs.MM) sub-categories.
